        <h3 style="margin:30px 0 0 30px">Star Wars: Rogue Squadron</h3>
        <p class="paragraph">This was my first ever game, modified from a template created by my professor during my first semester at BSU. I created the player and enemy models, added the stars and the Death Star in the background, and added a feature that would cause the player to loop to the opposite side of the playing field if they travelled too far. I also added the feature that if the player were to drop to a low enough hp level, they would be able to speed up by holding down the shift key to flee to safety. Though at the time I was well aware of the fact that this title was already copyrighted by Factor 5 and Lucasarts, this was my first ever game and I couldn't think of any better name for it. Given that this was my first ever game and would not be sold for profit, I didn't worry about using the same name.</p>
        <embed src="/assets/Survive.swf" width="999px" height="600px" style="display:block; margin-left:auto; margin-right:auto"></embed>
        <h3 style="margin:30px 0 0 30px">Isabella Jones</h3>
        <p class="paragraph">This was my second game, and my first group project. We decided to make a spinoff character based on Indiana Jones and make a stereotypical dungeon-shooter-platformer where you use your lantern and a pistol to shoot down nazis and find the treasure at the end of the tomb. I created all of the artwork you see in this game, with the exception of the enemies. I also programmed the levels to be procedurally generated, so that the previous level disappears once you cross the screen and a new level appears. It was actually quite difficult but I made it work. My classmate, Justin, programmed the character animations, the flashlight effect, the healthbar, the ammunition, and the movement. Sam collected the audio files for us.</p>
